Post-quantum signature schemes such as ML-DSA impose public keys and signatures an order of magnitude larger than their elliptic-curve counterparts, substantially increasing communication and storage costs. An alternative approach replaces signature verification with hash-based authorization: a prover demonstrates knowledge of a secret preimage tied to a public commitment, rather than presenting a signature. This sidesteps lattice-based operations entirely, requiring only hash evaluations and membership proofs.

We formalize this approach as a wormhole proof system: funds are committed to addresses derived from secret preimages, then later claimed by proving knowledge of the preimage without revealing it. We construct a recursive proof architecture using Plonky2 with FRI commitments, enabling aggregation of many authorization proofs into a single succinct proof. To provide privacy against balance-linking adversaries, we introduce dummy padding with local shuffling at the first aggregation layer, enlarging the effective anonymity set.

We provide game-based security proofs for six properties: deposit binding, one-time withdrawal, spend-path exclusivity, value conservation, nullifier indistinguishability, and transaction unlinkability. Our analysis bounds adversarial advantage in terms of anonymity set size and shows that computing this size is #P-hard. Benchmarks demonstrate 20ms proving time per authorization with 1.6ms verification, scaling to 256 authorizations via two-layer aggregation with constant-time (3.7ms) final verification.
